What is the DP approach for Word Break?

```
FUNCTION WordBreak(s, wordDict):
    n = LENGTH(s)
    dp = ARRAY[n + 1] filled with false
    dp[0] = true  // empty string

    for i = 1 to n:
        for j = 0 to i-1:
            if dp[j] AND s[j:i] IN wordDict:
                dp[i] = true
                break

    return dp[n]

FUNCTION WordBreakAll(s, wordDict):
    memo = HASH_MAP
    return WordBreakHelper(s, wordDict, memo)

FUNCTION WordBreakHelper(s, wordDict, memo):
    if s IN memo:
        return memo[s]

    if EMPTY(s):
        return ['']

    result = []
    for word in wordDict:
        if s.STARTS_WITH(word):
            suffix = s[LENGTH(word):]
            suffixBreaks = WordBreakHelper(suffix, wordDict, memo)
            for suffixBreak in suffixBreaks:
                result.ADD(word + (' ' + suffixBreak if suffixBreak else ''))

    memo[s] = result
    return result
```

How does wildcard pattern matching work?

```
FUNCTION IsMatch(s, p):
    m = LENGTH(s)
    n = LENGTH(p)
    dp = 2D_ARRAY[m+1][n+1] filled with false

    dp[0][0] = true  // empty matches empty

    // Handle patterns like a* or *a* etc.
    for j = 1 to n:
        if p[j-1] == '*':
            dp[0][j] = dp[0][j-1]

    for i = 1 to m+1:
        for j = 1 to n+1:
            if p[j-1] == '*':
                dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j] OR dp[i][j-1]
            else if p[j-1] == '?' OR s[i-1] == p[j-1]:
                dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1]

    return dp[m][n]
```

What is the approach for Lowest Common Ancestor in Binary Tree?

```
FUNCTION LowestCommonAncestor(root, p, q):
    if root == NULL OR root == p OR root == q:
        return root

    left = LowestCommonAncestor(root.left, p, q)
    right = LowestCommonAncestor(root.right, p, q)

    if left != NULL AND right != NULL:
        return root  // p and q in different subtrees

    return left if left != NULL else right

// For BST - more efficient
FUNCTION LCAinBST(root, p, q):
    while root != NULL:
        if p.val < root.val AND q.val < root.val:
            root = root.left
        else if p.val > root.val AND q.val > root.val:
            root = root.right
        else:
            return root  // split point or one of p,q
    return NULL
```

What is Johnson's algorithm for?

